      heading: 'CHAPTER TWENTY-SEVEN',
      content: '<p>The Formation Practices \u2014 What the Aligned Life Actually Requires</p>' +
        '<p>THE COMPASS PROVIDES THE ORIENTATION. The formation practices provide the movement.</p>' +
        '<p>Every tradition examined in this book has understood that the compass without the practices is philosophy without formation \u2014 the articulation of the moral order without the disciplines through which the moral order is embedded in the character of the person who has encountered it. Aristotle understood it: virtue is not knowledge but habit, and habits are formed through practice rather than through instruction. The early communities understood it: the formation of genuine character requires the sustained practice of specific disciplines within the communal context that makes those disciplines possible. The monastic tradition understood it: the Benedictine Rule\u2019s organization of every dimension of communal life around the regular rehearsal of the formation practices was not an excess of institutional control but the recognition that genuine formation requires the structuring of time, space, and relationship around the practices that produce it.</p>' +
        '<p>The contemporary moment\u2019s primary moral deficit is not the absence of moral frameworks. It is the absence of formation practices \u2014 the specific disciplines through which the settled truths of the Alignment Compass are embedded in the character of the person who has committed to the journey from South toward True North. Information about the moral life is available in unprecedented abundance. The practices through which moral information becomes moral formation are available in unprecedented scarcity.</p>' +
        '<p>This chapter describes those practices \u2014 drawing on the full range of traditions examined in the historical argument, identifying the common thread that runs through every formation tradition the human record has produced, and commending their application in the specific conditions of the contemporary moment with the honesty that the urgency of the situation requires.</p>'
