        '<p>This claim is not primarily theological, though it has theological implications that I do not want to minimize. It is historical and philosophical \u2014 grounded in the specific evidence that Part Three examined with the same analytical seriousness applied to every other civilization and every other moral teacher in the book. The wilderness temptation\u2019s engagement of all three drivers at maximum pressure without fracture. The complete correspondence of the inner and outer life across the full range of the gospel tradition\u2019s evidence. The cross\u2019s survival of maximum pressure on every driver simultaneously with the orientation toward True North. The recognition of the communities that formed around his life that what they had encountered was not a moral teacher of extraordinary formation but the fully aligned life itself.</p>' +
        '<p>I believe this claim. Not merely as an analytical conclusion from the evidence, though the evidence supports it. I believe it as a person who has been attempting, with the imperfect and ongoing effort that every honest engagement with the formation journey requires, to orient my own life toward the standard that the one example embodies. And I can tell you, from the inside of that attempt, that the orientation matters \u2014 that the difference between the formation journey aimed at an abstract ideal and the formation journey oriented toward a specific person, whose specific choices in specific circumstances demonstrate with extraordinary precision what the governed life looks like under real pressure, is the difference between having a map of the territory and having a guide who has walked it.</p>' +
        '<p>He walked it. The historical record preserves, in sufficient detail to be genuinely useful, the account of how he walked it \u2014 what he said, what he did, how he treated the people whose lives intersected with his, how he engaged the drivers when the circumstances pressed them toward their ungoverned expression, and what he produced in the quality of his common life with the specific people around him that made them willing, in the end, to reorganize their entire understanding of the moral order around the evidence of what they had observed.</p>'
